SIMPLE: lug
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lug
<hw>Lug</hw> <pr>(l⟦ucr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sw. <ets>lugg</ets>
the forelock.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The ear, or its lobe.</def>
<mark>[Scot. & Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which projects like an ear, esp. that by which
anything is supported, carried, or grasped, or to which a support is
fastened; an ear; <as>as, the <ex>lugs</ex> of a kettle; the
<ex>lugs</ex> of a founder's flask; the <ex>lug</ex> (handle) of a
jug.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A projecting piece to which
anything, as a rod, is attached, or against which anything, as a wedge
or key, bears, or through which a bolt passes, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Harness)</fld> <def>The leather loop or ear by
which a shaft is held up.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The lugworm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A man; sometimes implying clumsiness.</def>
<mark>[slang]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Lug bolt</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a bolt
terminating in a long, flat extension which takes the place of a head; a
strap bolt.</cd> -- <col><b>Lug nut</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a
large nut fitting a heavy bolt; -- used especially of the nuts used to
attach wheels to vehicles.</cd> -- <col><b>Lug wrench</b></col>
<fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a wrench used to tighten or loosen lug nuts,
usually a steel rod having a hexagonally shaped socket which fits
closely over the lug nut; sometimes in the shape of a cross, having
several such sockets, one at the end of each arm, to accommodate nuts of
different sizes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lug
<hw>Lug</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Lugged</conjf> <pr>(l⟦ucr⟧gd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Lugging</conjf> <pr>(l⟦ucr⟧g"g⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>luggen</ets>, Sw. <ets>lugga</ets> to pull by the hair, fr.
<ets>lugg</ets> the forelock.]</ety> <def>To pull with force; to haul;
to drag along; to carry with difficulty, as something heavy or
cumbersome.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They must divide the image among them, and so <qex>lug</qex> off
every one his share.</q> <rj><qau>Collier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lug
<hw>Lug</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To move slowly and
heavily.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Lug
<hw>Lug</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of lugging; <as>as,
a hard <ex>lug</ex></as>; that which is lugged; <as>as, the pack is a
heavy <ex>lug</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything which moves slowly.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Ascham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Lug
<hw>Lug</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A rod or pole.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Wright.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A measure of length, being 16⟦frac12⟧ feet; a rod,
pole, or perch.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧ Eight <xex>lugs</xex>
of ground.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Chimney lug</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Lug
pole</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a pole on which a kettle is hung over the
fire, either in a chimney or in the open air.</cd> <mark>[Local,
U.S.]</mark> <rj><au>Whittier.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Luganda</ent>⟦br⟧
